segments.text: and muster and silver taps and things like that.
When you came back, everybody was determined, as you are getting ready to graduate, tell me about getting a job and things like that.
What was the job market?
The job market was a big...
I guess if I had to overall look, I could say it was a circus.
Wendell Horsley had fine-tuned the job application process, and he provided us.
I have a little portrait, a print cut, a printed resume,
In my case, I was a distinguished student in a degree in mechanical engineering.
Dr. Gilchrist had arranged for me to get a fellowship to go to Purdue.
And I felt like that would be a tough road to hold.
year-and-a-half old, almost two-year-old son, and no money.
So I thanked him profusely and went ahead to my applications, and I interviewed, I had ten job offers to have more.

I took the job offered by Humboldt and a planning company, Exxon, because it was slightly more money, but at the time it was a company that I had most confidence in would still be there as long as I wanted to be there.
Do you remember what that starting salary was?
Yeah, it was $2.37 an hour on a drilling drill.
Cool.
And you graduated?
This was January of 1947.
Tell me about the commencement ceremony.
I don't think there was one.
I wasn't there.
I'd gone to get my job lined up.
I went down to Houston and they told me to come back in several days and I went back and
Got things set with Virginia and Little Rock and then I went back and they told me to go over to Beaumont.
Did you get, where, how did you obtain your diploma?
Was it mailed to you or do you remember?
Yeah, as I recall it was mailed to me.
Let's see, one of that I remember, see that I missed was Bonfire.
Was there a Bonfire held in those days?
Oh yeah.
Where was it?
It was in the middle of the drill field.
Okay.
For example, when I was a freshman, it was mandatory on the freshman to scout the wood for the bonfire in the months of October and early November.
And the guys in my outfit, we discovered a
a lonesome telephone pole down there north of Northgate.
It was out in the vacant lot.
It looked kind of malty.
So we undertook to appropriate that pole.
Some folks put a lot of concrete around the bottom of it.
So it took us, I guess, about two weeks of rocking that thing back and forth to
It took two weeks of rocking that thing back and forth before we could finally pull it out of the ground.
And then we hauled it up there and laid our stack on the pile.
So it was a pile then of... No more than one telephone pole high.
Okay.
A telephone pole not as tall as a black pole.
All right.
And there was not paper.
Somehow they always found a chick sail to go on top.
That's what I've heard.
Now, there was no...
No trash paper or cardboard?
No.
It was all wood, but it was not stacked up, organized like it is now?
Oh, no.
Nobody was in charge.
Everybody made their contribution as they saw fit.
Did the whole student body turn out for it?
Oh, yeah.
I guess it was after I came back from it.
Texas Corps tried to firebomb it from an airplane, but that didn't happen.
They always had the chick saying, and it wasn't a big deal.
Where did that, where did those words come from?
The chick saying?
Oh, that's a long, long thing to say.
It sure didn't have anything to do with anything.
Okay.
The most important question of all.
Now as you look back, what did it mean to you and your life that you went to A&M?
What effect did it have?
Well, the greatest thing that could happen to me, I'll forever be grateful for the opportunity.
I went to A&M, I had the opportunity to
who get an education, literally thousands of friends, and have had the opportunity to lead several causes that have, I think, bolstered respect for me, and just to serve all that come their way.
I could have gone, I had applications to MIT, Caltech, Stanford, but I collected for reasons of either housing or otherwise, or not to try, but I had a good start.
I was really humble.
Thank you, thank you.
Let's quit there.
